top valence band and a relatively smaller downshift of the bottom conduction band.

Interestingly, in the case of Li, Na, K, Tl, O, and S, an indirect gap has been induced, as a result of a bump on the top valence band along the $\Gamma-X$ direction. Similar bump can also be observed in the case of $\mathrm{Ni}$, but a defect band forms the top valence band covering the bump so that the band gap is still direct. In the case of $\mathrm{Rb}$, the band structure is significantly different from the other group IA elements, the top valence band is shifted up, resulting in significantly reduced band gap.

Trilayer BP. So far, F is the only case that does not work for either monolayer or bilayer BP. We studied F-decorated trilayer BP. Our results show that F-decoration can shift the CBM of trilayer BP below the $\mathrm{O}_{2} / \mathrm{O}_{2}{ }^{-}$redox potential. Similar to the case of $\mathrm{Cl}$ on monolayer BP, $\mathrm{F}$ adatom also introduces two midgap states inside the band gap of pristine trilayer BP and results in spin polarization. From the band structure and DOS in Fig. 8, it\\
